Great, let's begin!

First, we need to create a repository on GitHub, which will host the website. Here's how to create a new repository on GitHub:

1. Log in to your GitHub account and click the "New" button on the repositories page.

2. Give your repository a name, such as "nick-worthy-website", and add a short description if desired.

3. Choose "Public" for the visibility setting, so that your website is visible to anyone with its URL.

4. Check the "Initialize this repository with a README" box, which will create a README.md file in the repository.

5. Click the "Create repository" button to create the new repository.

Next, we'll clone this repository to our local machine and get started with adding the necessary files and content.

Here are the steps to clone the repository:

1. Open your command-line interface and navigate to the directory where you want to save your website files.

2. Type the following command to clone the repository to your local machine:

```
git clone https://github.com/<your-github-username>/nick-worthy-website.git
```

Note: Replace <your-github-username> with your actual GitHub username.

3. Change into the new directory by typing `cd nick-worthy-website`.

Now, we can add the necessary files and content to the repository.

First, let's add the HTML file. Create a new file called `index.html` in the root of the project directory and copy and paste the example HTML code I provided earlier into the file.

Next, we'll add a CSS file to style the HTML. Create a new file called `style.css` in the same directory and add the following code to apply some basic styling to the website:

```
body {
    font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', sans-serif;
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.5;
    background-color: #f2f2f2;
}

header {
    background-color: #222;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 1rem;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
}

nav ul {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
}

nav li {
    margin: 0 1rem;
}

.hero {
    padding: 5rem 1rem 3rem;
    margin: 0 auto;
    text-align: center;
    color: #fff;
    background: url('https://source.unsplash.com/random/1600x900') center/cover no-repeat;
}

.hero h2 {
    font-size: 3rem;
    line-height: 1.2;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
}

.hero p {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
}

.cta {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 0.5rem 1rem;
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    background-color: #f8b617;
    color: #222;
    text-decoration: none; 
    border-radius: 4px;
    margin-top: 1rem;
}

main {
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2rem;
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
    background-color: #fff;
    box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.15);
}

section {
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
}

section h2 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    font-weight: normal;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
}

article {
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
}

article h3 {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
}

article p {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
}

article a {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    display: block;
    margin-top: 1rem;
}

footer {
    background-color: #222;
    color: #fff;
    text-align: center;
    padding: 1rem;
    margin-top: 3rem;
}
```

After adding the HTML and CSS files, it's time to push these changes to the repository.

Here are the steps to push the changes to the remote GitHub repository:

1. In your command-line interface, navigate to the root of the project directory.

2. Stage the changes by typing the following command:

```
git add .
```

3. Commit the changes with a meaningful commit message by typing the following command:

```
git commit -m "Add HTML and CSS files for the website"
```

